Rating: 4
We have made this many times to rave reviews. It's one of our favorite dishes--with lots of freshly ground black pepper! I plan on making this for Valentine's Day this year. This is the classic alfredo sauce; if you put in garlic or nutmeg, it ceases to be alfredo sauce. It is essential to use freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese--powdered parmesan will give awful results--and real heavy (also called whipping) cream (at least 35% butterfat). In a simple dish like this, it is the quality of the ingredients that make or break the meal. To "A Cook from Chicago," a white sauce (aka béchamel) is made with a roux of flour and butter with milk whisked in and is in no way the same thing as an alfredo sauce. A white sauce to which cheese has been added is called a mornay sauce.

